            <pb n="1R"/>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <placeName>Syracuse N. Y.</placeName>
                <date>7 October 1852</date>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">Dear Sir!</p>
            <p>In accordance to your request, and deeming it<lb/> a duty, I hereby tender you a
                report of the<lb/> proceedings of our congregation, “Cheneseth Shalom”<lb/> within
                the late holidays.</p>
            <p>The synagogue was well attended and two<lb/> sermons were delivered by out most
                worthy<lb/> minister <persName>Rev. H. A. Henry</persName>—one on
                    Bimtenhal<add>?</add><lb/>
                <date>Sabbath</date>, &amp; the other during the festival of
                <date>Succoth</date>.<lb/> They were delivered in a manner which delighted<lb/> the
                entire audience present, &amp; give great<lb/> Credit, to <persName>Mr.
                    H.</persName> The prayers were read<lb/> on <add>ראש השנה</add> and <add>יום
                    כפור</add> by <persName>Mr H</persName> in a very<lb/> impressive style which
                not only satisfied the con=<lb/>gregation but impressed them with a feeling<lb/> of
                true devotion. The synagogue was attended<lb/> by many strangers from different
                parts of the<lb/> state, who in concert with our members have<lb/> contributed very
                liberally towards the support<lb/> of the Synagogue, promoted as they declared<lb/>
                themselves highly pleased with our <sic>procedings</sic>.—<lb/> A<add>?</add> few
                weeks ago our highly respected President<lb/>
                <persName>Jacob Stone</persName> resigned, whereupon <persName>Mr Isaac H
                    Bronner</persName></p>
            <pb n="1V"/>
            <p>was elected President &amp; <persName>Mr. M. Corre<add>?</add></persName><lb/> V.
                Pres:; every thing in our congregation<lb/> appears to work well towards the
                prosperity<lb/> knowing how happy you are to record<lb/> the deserved merits of the
                ministers of<lb/> our Religion I have to inform You that<lb/> our Ministers time
                expired on the <date>1st<lb/> of October</date>, &amp; he had signified his
                instructions<lb/> to retire from this City, having had overtures<lb/> made to him,
                to take an other office much<lb/> more lucrative than ours, and a much<lb/> larger
                congregation. But such is the estimation<lb/> in which he is held by our
                congregation &amp;<lb/> by the unani<del>n</del>mous voice of the members<lb/> he
                was prevailed upon to remain among<lb/> us to which he kindly consented.</p>
            <p>The members acted <sic>jutisciarisly</sic> in their<lb/> choice, convinced that the
                affairs of the<lb/> congregation have been materially <sic>beniffited</sic><lb/>
                during his administrations, of which we<lb/> had sufficient proof during the late
                holidays.<lb/> To show you what the feeling of the congregation<lb/> is towards
                    <persName>Mr. H.</persName> I will say in short:<lb/> that they wish to engage
                his services for as<lb/> long as teperiod<add>?</add> as he may feel disposed;<lb/>
                in opposition to the usual <sic>costinnes</sic> in<lb/> the states of electing
                minsters annually.<lb/> I regret not to have been enabled to get</p>
            <pb n="2R"/>
            <p>any new subscribers for the Occident<lb/> I should feel obliged by your
                publishing<lb/> this letter if you think it worthy a<lb/> place in the next number
                of your magazine.</p>
            <p rend="indent(4)">Yours truly</p>
            <p rend="indent(5)">
                <persName role="author">S Lenn</persName>
            </p>
            <p>
                <addressee>Isaac Leeser Esq.</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Editor of the Occident</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)"><placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>.</p>
            <p>PS. Haben Sie Guts<add>?</add> meinen Namen<lb/> nicht ins Volle zu ziechnen
                sondern<lb/> nur Z. &amp; solthen Sie Schreibfehler oder<lb/> sonstige unrechte
                ausdrücke darin finden<lb/> so verbessern Sie es gehs und bedenken<lb/> Sie daß ich
                in der englischen Sprache keine<lb/> so gut Fortschritte zu machen in Hande bin<lb/>
                als Sie es in <persName>Herrn <add>?</add>ugend</persName> waren.</p>
            <p><date>Oct 11<hi rend="sup">th</hi></date>., <add>?</add> sprech ich mit <add>?</add><lb/>
                <persName>Jacob Stone</persName> welches mir sagte daß<lb/> es Ihren in kurze selbst
                schreiben<lb/> wird<lb/>
                <persName>D.O.</persName></p>
